In a small area of my yard I made a most exciting discovery this year. I left the area to grow and found orchids growing right in the lawn under a small power line that runs through the property. These are called southern slender ladies-tresses (Spiranthes lacera). They were poking up like tiny spiral staircases out of the grass.

Orchids...growing right by my house...I had no clue were there! I was thrilled! 

The area will have to remain clear under the power line but I will only mow it now once a year (March is the best time so as to promote wildlife and pollinator habitat the rest of the year). 

I share this because I truly think the most important step we can take as land stewards is to get to know the land we live on. Learn what‚Äôs there, what‚Äôs growing, who‚Äôs visiting. And daily I am surprised and delighted by what I find. My knowledge of the flora and fauna around me has been ESSENTIAL to inform my land management decisions. Not to mention it‚Äôs just so fun! 

Lawns are just so ...boring! üòÜ but seriously. For us and for wildlife.

