The Great Monarch Migration:

The eggs and caterpillars that you are seeing now in your gardens are a third or even fourth generation and are known as the super-generation. This generation has an astonishing life span of 8-9 months compared to the 6-8 weeks of the earlier summer generations. Their larger size is due to increased body fat needed to fuel the 5,000 km migration down to Mexico.

After overwintering there, they migrate again, to Texas, where they will mate, lay eggs, and die. This is the beginning of the multiple-generation journey to Ontario and other points in Canada east of the Rockies. Imagine, the Monarchs we are seeing now could be the great-great grandchildren of last September‚Äôs Monarchs!

